I"S<p>Benefits of Code Review</p>

<p>Multiple eyes on a piece of code. Finding bugs early.
Coding standards compliance
Consistent design and implementation. Better Structured code.
Team cohesion
Learn how to write better code
Teaching and Sharing Knowledge. Mentoring tool.</p>

<p>Guidelines for Authors
 Before raising PR:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Code is ‚Äúcomplete as possible‚Äù</li>
  <li>Small Pull Request.</li>
  <li>In case of Long Request, ‚ÄúPoint out important parts‚Äù</li>
  <li>Explain changes in PR Description along with JIRA story links</li>
  <li>Read the checklist and mark the things which you have considered for this PR</li>
  <li>Pull Request Title : Use JIRA ticket and useful title description</li>
</ul>

<p>After Raising PR:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Be grateful for the reviewer‚Äôs suggestions.
 e.g. Good call. I‚Äôll make that change., Whoops. Good catch, thanks. Fixed in a4994ec.</li>
  <li>A common axiom is ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt take it personally. The review is of the code, not you.‚Äù</li>
  <li>Try to respond to every comment.</li>
</ul>

<p>Guidelines for Reviewers</p>
<ul>
  <li>Don‚Äôt nitpick - Focus on the correctness of code. Less focus whitespaces/variable names.</li>
  <li>Don‚Äôt be a jerk - No harsh comments plz</li>
  <li>Ask good questions; don‚Äôt make demands.</li>
  <li>Avoid selective ownership of code. (‚Äúmine‚Äù, ‚Äúnot mine‚Äù, ‚Äúyours‚Äù)</li>
  <li>Provide Examples  ( Small code snippets will do )</li>
  <li>Seek first to understand</li>
</ul>

<p>Tools and General Advise:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Schedule time for PR‚Äôs</li>
  <li>Automate with code linting</li>
  <li>Use a checklist</li>
</ul>

